  <p><strong>Quick Summary:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>DonnEase adaptive compression socks build the donning solution into the sock itself, using a numbered guide system (#2, #3, blue dot).</li>
    <li>No external devices needed. The wide-mouth opening is approximately three times wider than standard compression socks.</li>
    <li>Integrated pull-tabs replace the need for grip strength.</li>
    <li>The system works for people with limited dexterity, one-handed use, cognitive changes, and caregiver-assisted application.</li>
    <li>True graduated compression is maintained, unlike zipper socks.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Research suggests that 30 to 65 percent of people prescribed compression socks stop wearing them. The most common reason isn't that compression doesn't work. It's that the socks are too difficult to put on. For people living with arthritis, spinal cord injury, stroke, tremors, or age-related changes in hand strength, standard compression socks can feel like a daily battle. The adaptive compression socks industry has tried to solve this with external tools: metal donning frames, friction slides, zipper modifications. But AccessAble took a different approach. Instead of building a tool to wrestle a poorly designed sock onto your foot, we redesigned the sock. DonnEase was what happened when we stopped asking "how do we make donning easier?" and started asking "why is it hard in the first place?"</p>

  <h2>The Problem DonnEase Was Built to Solve</h2>

  <p>Graduated compression works by applying the tightest pressure at the ankle and gradually decreasing pressure up the calf. This pressure gradient is what may help support healthy circulation. But it also means the ankle opening of every compression sock is engineered to resist stretching. That's the fundamental tension: the feature that makes compression effective is the same feature that makes it difficult to put on.</p>

  <p>The compression sock industry's answer has been external donning aids. Each has tradeoffs:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Metal donning frames (sock butlers):</strong> Require you to step into a rigid frame, then pull the sock up from the frame. They're bulky, can't travel easily, and many users find them awkward or undignified. They also require significant hand strength to remove the sock from the frame afterward.</li>
    <li><strong>Friction slide devices:</strong> A slippery sleeve that reduces friction as you slide the sock on. Effective for some users, but removing the sleeve from inside the sock after donning still requires dexterity, which is the exact problem you're trying to solve.</li>
    <li><strong>Zipper compression socks:</strong> A zipper running up the side makes the sock easy to open wide. But the zipper breaks the graduated compression profile. The pressure is no longer consistent around the full circumference of the leg, which reduces the sock's ability to support healthy circulation.</li>
    <li><strong>Velcro compression wraps (CircAid, FarrowWrap):</strong> These work well for many users and provide genuine compression support. But they cost $100 to $200 per leg, they look distinctly medical, and they require precise wrapping technique to achieve correct compression. For people who want compression that looks like a normal sock, wraps are a functional but visible compromise.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The insight behind DonnEase was simple: if the barrier to wearing compression is the sock itself, the solution should be built into the sock. Not bolted on, not sold separately, not requiring a second device. Every adaptive feature is integrated into the garment, and the graduated compression profile stays intact.</p>

  <h2>How the Numbered Guide System Works</h2>

  <p>Most compression socks are a featureless tube of fabric. There's no way to tell top from bottom, front from back, or where to grip. For someone with full dexterity, this is a minor annoyance. For someone with limited hand function, cognitive fatigue, or a caregiver who's never applied compression before, it's a real barrier.</p>

  <p>The DonnEase numbered guide system solves this with three visual markers:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Blue dot (toe area):</strong> The orientation marker. The blue dot always faces up, on top of the foot. Before you do anything else, find the blue dot. If it's facing up, the sock is correctly oriented. This single marker removes the most common donning mistake: putting the sock on twisted or inside out.</li>
    <li><strong>#3 marker with "PULL TO ANKLE" (lower cuff):</strong> Your first grip point. After orienting with the blue dot, find the #3 marker. This is where you grab to pull the sock over your foot and seat it at the ankle. The wide-mouth opening at this point is approximately three times wider than a standard compression sock, which dramatically reduces the resistance during the hardest part of donning.</li>
    <li><strong>#2 marker with "PULL TO KNEE" (upper cuff):</strong> Your second grip point. Once the sock is seated at the ankle, find the #2 marker. Grip here and pull upward to position the sock along your calf to just below the knee. The integrated pull-tabs at this marker provide a textured grip surface that doesn't require strong pinching force.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The numbering isn't random. It follows the order of donning: orient (blue dot), anchor at ankle (#3), pull to knee (#2). This sequence matters for four reasons:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Cognitive accessibility:</strong> On mornings when fatigue, brain fog, or medication side effects make complex tasks harder, numbered steps remove guesswork. You don't need to remember technique. You follow the numbers.</li>
    <li><strong>Caregiver consistency:</strong> A family member, home health aide, or clinical professional can learn the system in under a minute. The markers tell them exactly where to grip and how far to pull.</li>
    <li><strong>Visual confirmation:</strong> You can see from across the room whether a sock is positioned correctly. If the #2 marker is at the knee and the blue dot is on top, it's right.</li>
    <li><strong>Step-by-step pacing:</strong> Instead of one long, exhausting pull from toe to knee, the system breaks donning into two manageable stages. Anchor at ankle, rest if needed, then pull to knee.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Step-by-Step: Donning with the DonnEase System</h2>

  <p>These steps work whether you're donning independently or with a caregiver's help. For detailed techniques specific to seated donning, one-handed use, or low-dexterity strategies, see our <a href="/learn/how-to-put-on-compression-socks-easily">complete donning guide with 5 adaptive methods</a>.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Find the blue dot.</strong> Hold the sock with the blue dot facing up (toward the ceiling). This confirms correct orientation.</li>
    <li><strong>Invert the sock to the #3 marker.</strong> Reach inside the sock, grab the heel pocket, and fold the upper portion down over itself until you can see the #3 "PULL TO ANKLE" marker at the opening.</li>
    <li><strong>Slide your foot in and anchor at the ankle.</strong> With the wide-mouth opening facing you, slide your toes in and position the heel pocket. Use the #3 marker as your grip point and pull until the sock is seated at the ankle.</li>
    <li><strong>Pull to the #2 marker.</strong> Grip the pull-tabs near the #2 "PULL TO KNEE" marker and pull the sock upward along your calf. Use steady, even pressure on both sides.</li>
    <li><strong>Smooth and check.</strong> Once the sock reaches just below the knee, smooth any wrinkles flat. Verify: blue dot is on top of the foot, #3 marker is at the ankle area, #2 marker is just below the knee.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Who Is DonnEase Designed For?</h2>

  <p>DonnEase was designed for the people that standard compression socks were not. That includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>People with arthritis or hand weakness:</strong> The wide-mouth opening means less grip force is needed. Pull-tabs replace the need to pinch and grip slippery compression fabric. Over 54 million adults in the U.S. live with arthritis.</li>
    <li><strong>People with spinal cord injury:</strong> AccessAble's founder, Cody Coffey, has a C4 incomplete spinal cord injury. DonnEase was designed from that lived experience. The numbered markers work with limited hand function.</li>
    <li><strong>Stroke survivors and people with hemiplegia:</strong> One-handed donning is possible with the guide system because the markers tell you exactly where to grab with your functional hand.</li>
    <li><strong>People recovering from surgery:</strong> Restricted bending and limited reach after hip, knee, or back surgery make standard sock donning difficult. The wide opening and pull-tabs mean you can get the sock on from a seated position without bending as far.</li>
    <li><strong>Older adults and their caregivers:</strong> Age-related changes in grip strength, flexibility, and balance affect donning ability. For caregivers, the numbered system removes the need for training time.</li>
    <li><strong>Anyone who has given up on compression:</strong> If you've been prescribed compression socks but stopped wearing them because they're too hard to put on, DonnEase was built for exactly that situation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Makes DonnEase Different from Other "Easy" Socks</h2>

  <p>Several products market themselves as easy to put on. Here's an honest comparison:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Zipper socks:</strong> Easy to open, but the zipper interrupts graduated compression. Zippers can also pinch skin and snag during donning.</li>
    <li><strong>Velcro wraps:</strong> Genuinely effective compression and easier to apply than traditional socks. But they cost $100 to $200 per leg and look distinctly medical.</li>
    <li><strong>Donning frames and butlers:</strong> Work for people with limited bending but adequate hand strength. However, they're bulky and can't travel with you.</li>
    <li><strong>Friction slides and sleeves:</strong> Reduce resistance during application. But you still need dexterity to remove the slide from inside the sock after donning.</li>
    <li><strong>DonnEase:</strong> No external device. Adaptive features are built into the sock. Wide-mouth opening (3x standard), integrated pull-tabs, numbered guide system. Maintains true graduated compression. Looks like a premium compression sock when worn.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>This isn't to say that other solutions don't work. Velcro wraps are an excellent choice for many people. Donning frames help users with good hand strength but limited bending. DonnEase fills a specific gap: compression that's easier to put on without sacrificing compression quality or requiring an external tool.</p>

  <h2>Compression Levels Available</h2>

  <p>The DonnEase numbered guide system is available across AccessAble's compression range:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>8-15 mmHg (Gentle Wellness):</strong> Light support for everyday comfort. A good starting point for people trying compression for the first time.</li>
    <li><strong>15-20 mmHg (Everyday Relief):</strong> Moderate support that may help manage minor swelling and fatigue from prolonged sitting or standing.</li>
    <li><strong>20-30 mmHg (Medical Support):</strong> Firmer support often recommended by healthcare providers. Consult your healthcare provider before using this level.</li>
    <li><strong>30-40 mmHg (Firm Medical):</strong> High compression used under direct medical supervision. Always consult your healthcare provider before using this level.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The numbered guide system works the same way regardless of compression level. The adaptive features don't affect the compression profile.</p>

  <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>DonnEase builds the donning solution into the sock itself. No external frames, slides, or devices required.</li>
    <li>The numbered guide system (blue dot, #3 PULL TO ANKLE, #2 PULL TO KNEE) breaks donning into clear, repeatable steps.</li>
    <li>The wide-mouth opening is approximately three times wider than standard compression socks.</li>
    <li>True graduated compression is maintained. Unlike zipper socks, the adaptive features don't compromise the compression profile.</li>
    <li>If you've stopped wearing compression because it's too hard to put on, DonnEase was designed for exactly that situation. Consult your healthcare provider about the right compression level for you.</li>
  </ul>

